1
00:00:06,798 --> 00:00:26,379
The column is the talk given by the Venerable Mahasi Syada, Eka Mahapandita Kusopana, given to his disciples on their induction into Vipassana meditation at Sasanajita Meditation Center, Jango, Myanmar.

2
00:00:28,242 --> 00:00:35,691
Practical Vipassana Meditational Exercises The practice of Vipassana

3
00:00:35,941 --> 00:00:49,740
or inside meditation is the effort made by the meditator to understand correctly the nature of the psychophysical phenomena taking place in his own body.

4
00:00:50,722 --> 00:00:58,112
Physical phenomena are the things or objects which one clearly perceives around one.

5
00:00:58,972 --> 00:01:05,862
The whole of one's body that one clearly perceives constitutes a group of material qualities

6
00:01:06,096 --> 00:01:06,537
Rupa.

7
00:01:07,980 --> 00:01:15,390
Psychical or mental phenomena are acts of consciousness or awareness .

8
00:01:16,331 --> 00:01:29,691
These Nama Rupas are clearly perceived to be happening whenever they are seen, heard, smelled, tasted, touched or thought of.

9
00:01:30,972 --> 00:01:33,335
We must make ourselves aware of them

10
00:01:33,939 --> 00:02:03,373
Observing them and noting thus Seeing Seeing Hearing Hearing Smelling Smelling Tasting Tasting Touching Touching or Thinking Thinking Every time one sees, hears, smells, tastes, touches or thinks

11
00:02:03,960 --> 00:02:06,563
one should make a note of the fact.

12
00:02:07,605 --> 00:02:14,771
But in the beginning of one's practice one cannot make a note of every one of these happenings.

13
00:02:15,712 --> 00:02:26,364
One should, therefore, begin with noting those happenings which are conspicuous and easily perceivable.

14
00:02:27,525 --> 00:02:30,187
With every act of breathing

15
00:02:30,538 --> 00:02:37,246
the abdomen rises and falls, which movement is always evident.

16
00:02:38,247 --> 00:02:45,655
This is the material quality known as vajradhatu, the element of motion.

17
00:02:46,596 --> 00:02:56,326
One should begin by noting this movement, which may be done by the mind intently observing the abdomen.

18
00:02:57,116 --> 00:03:26,466
You will find the abdomen rising when you breathe in and falling when you breathe out The rising should be noted mentally as rising and the falling as falling If the movement is not evident by just noting it mentally keep touching the abdomen with the palm of your hand Do not alter the manner of your breathing neither slow it down

19
00:03:26,733 --> 00:03:28,414
nor make it faster.

20
00:03:29,074 --> 00:03:32,018
Do not breathe too vigorously either.

21
00:03:32,658 --> 00:03:36,902
You will tire if you change the manner of your breathing.

22
00:03:38,224 --> 00:03:45,312
Breathe steadily as usual and note the rising and falling of the abdomen as they occur.

23
00:03:46,072 --> 00:03:49,034
Note it mentally, not verbally.

24
00:03:49,895 --> 00:03:54,681
In Vipassana meditation, what you name or say doesn't matter.

25
00:03:55,268 --> 00:03:58,350
What really matters is to know or perceive.

26
00:03:59,211 --> 00:04:09,263
While noting the rising of the abdomen, do so from the beginning to the end of the movement, just as if you are seeing with your eyes.

27
00:04:10,003 --> 00:04:12,667
Do the same with the falling movement.

28
00:04:13,348 --> 00:04:20,675
Note the rising movement in such a way that your awareness of it is concurrent with the movement itself.

29
00:04:21,377 --> 00:04:24,600
The movement and the mental awareness of it

30
00:04:25,103 --> 00:04:34,293
should coincide in the same way as a stone thrown hits the target, similarly with the falling movement.

31
00:04:35,636 --> 00:04:41,362
Your mind may wander elsewhere while you are noting the abdominal movement.

32
00:04:42,004 --> 00:04:47,589
This must also be noted by mentally saying, wandering, wandering.

33
00:04:48,471 --> 00:04:54,738
When this has been noted once or twice, the mind stops wandering, in which case

34
00:04:55,192 --> 00:04:59,637
you go back to noting the rising and falling of the abdomen.

35
00:05:00,598 --> 00:05:05,324
If the mind reaches somewhere, note as reaching, reaching.

36
00:05:06,185 --> 00:05:10,189
Then go back to the rising and falling of the abdomen.

37
00:05:11,050 --> 00:05:16,517
If you imagine meeting somebody, note as meeting, meeting.

38
00:05:17,298 --> 00:05:19,841
Then back to the rising and falling.

39
00:05:20,622 --> 00:05:23,966
If you imagine meeting and talking to somebody,

40
00:05:24,487 --> 00:05:53,699
Note as talking, talking In short, whatever thought or reflection occurs should be noted If you imagine, note as imagining If you think, thinking If you plan, planning If you perceive, perceiving If you reflect, reflecting If you feel happy, happy

41
00:05:54,136 --> 00:05:56,278
If you feel bored, bored.

42
00:05:56,899 --> 00:05:58,903
If you feel glad, glad.

43
00:05:59,483 --> 00:06:02,067
If you feel disheartened, disheartened.

44
00:06:03,028 --> 00:06:08,076
Noting all these acts of consciousness is called Sita Nupasana.

45
00:06:09,677 --> 00:06:18,391
Because we fail to note these acts of consciousness, we tend to identify them with a person or individual.

46
00:06:19,052 --> 00:06:23,517
We tend to think that it is I who is imagining.

47
00:06:23,903 --> 00:06:27,269
thinking, planning, knowing, or perceiving.

48
00:06:27,970 --> 00:06:34,961
We think that there is a person who from childhood onwards has been living and thinking.

49
00:06:35,783 --> 00:06:39,307
Actually, no such person exists.

50
00:06:40,209 --> 00:06:47,581
These are instead only these continuing and successive acts of consciousness.

51
00:06:47,966 --> 00:06:54,673
That is why we have to know these acts of consciousness and know them for what they are.

52
00:06:55,293 --> 00:07:02,399
That is why we have to note each and every act of consciousness as it arises.

53
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:06,202
When so noted, it tends to disappear.

54
00:07:06,803 --> 00:07:12,249
We then go back to noting the rising and falling of the active act.

55
00:07:14,411 --> 00:07:17,112
When you have sat meditating for long,

56
00:07:17,396 --> 00:07:22,882
sensations of stiffness and heat will arise in your body.

57
00:07:23,564 --> 00:07:25,966
These are to be noted carefully too.

58
00:07:26,747 --> 00:07:43,826
Similarly, with sensations of pain and tiredness, all of these sensations are Doka Viva Vedana, feeling of unsatisfactoriness, or noting them as Vedana Nupasana.

59
00:07:45,410 --> 00:08:03,072
Failure or omission to note these sensations makes you think, I am stiff, I am feeling hot, I am in pain, I was alright a moment ago, now I am uneasy with these unpleasant sensations.

60
00:08:04,372 --> 00:08:09,218
The identification of these sensations with the ego is mistaken.

61
00:08:09,839 --> 00:08:13,324
There is really no art involved.

62
00:08:13,709 --> 00:08:20,237
only a succession of one new unpleasant sensation after another.

63
00:08:20,276 --> 00:08:31,451
It is just like a continuous succession of new electrical impulses that light up electric lamps.

64
00:08:32,392 --> 00:08:43,125
Every time unpleasant contacts are encountered in the body, unpleasant sensations arise one after another.

65
00:08:43,527 --> 00:08:55,200
These sensations should be carefully and intently noted, whether they are sensations of stiffness, of heat, or of pain.

66
00:08:55,841 --> 00:09:07,894
In the beginning of the yogi's meditational practice, these sensations may tend to increase and lead to a desire to change his posture.

67
00:09:08,495 --> 00:09:10,918
This desire should be noted

68
00:09:11,269 --> 00:09:20,001
after which the yogi should go back to noting the sensation of stiffness, heat, etc.

69
00:09:22,205 --> 00:09:25,950
Patience leads to Nirvana, as the saying goes.

70
00:09:26,650 --> 00:09:31,197
This saying is most relevant in meditational effort.

71
00:09:32,177 --> 00:09:34,841
One must be patient in meditation.

72
00:09:35,643 --> 00:09:39,268
If one shifts or changes one's posture too often,

73
00:09:39,687 --> 00:09:51,418
Because one cannot be patient with the sensation of the stiffness or heat that arises, samadhi, good concentration, cannot develop.

74
00:09:52,278 --> 00:10:07,114
If samadhi cannot develop, insight cannot result, and there can be no attainment of mega, the path that leads to nirvana, phala, the fruit of that path, and nirvana.

75
00:10:08,615 --> 00:10:09,576
That is why

76
00:10:10,044 --> 00:10:12,729
Patience is needed in meditation.

77
00:10:13,450 --> 00:10:26,109
It is patience mostly with unpleasant sensations in the body like stiffness, sensations of heat and pain, and other sensations that are hard to bear.

78
00:10:26,850 --> 00:10:37,424
One should not immediately give up one's meditation on the appearance of such sensations and change one's meditational posture.

79
00:10:37,445 --> 00:10:39,427
One should go on patiently

80
00:10:39,727 --> 00:10:46,236
just noting as stiffness, stiffness, or heart, heart.

81
00:10:47,217 --> 00:10:53,586
Moderate sensations of these kinds will disappear if one goes on noting them patiently.

82
00:10:54,368 --> 00:11:01,057
When concentration is good and strong, even intense sensations tend to disappear.

83
00:11:01,817 --> 00:11:07,304
One then reverts to noting the rising and falling of the abdomen.

84
00:11:08,547 --> 00:11:09,668
One will of course

85
00:11:09,951 --> 00:11:24,173
have to change one's posture if the sensations do not disappear, even after one has noted them for a long time, and if, on the other hand, they become unbearable.

86
00:11:25,474 --> 00:11:30,841
One should then begin noting as wishing to change, wishing to change.

87
00:11:31,482 --> 00:11:35,929
If the arm rises, notice rising, rising.

88
00:11:36,650 --> 00:11:39,654
If it moves, notice moving,

89
00:11:39,854 --> 00:11:40,394
moving.

90
00:11:41,296 --> 00:11:53,048
This change should be made gently and know that it is rising, rising, moving, moving, and touching, touching.

91
00:11:55,431 --> 00:11:59,195
If the body sways, swaying, swaying.

92
00:12:00,135 --> 00:12:03,578
If the foot rises, rising, rising.

93
00:12:04,340 --> 00:12:07,182
If it moves, moving, moving.

94
00:12:07,943 --> 00:12:08,865
If it drops,

95
00:12:09,250 --> 00:12:10,871
dropping, dropping.

96
00:12:11,972 --> 00:12:20,501
If there is no change but only static rest, go back to noting the rising and falling of the abdomen.

97
00:12:21,482 --> 00:12:37,519
There must be no intermission in between, only contiguity between a preceding act of noting and a succeeding one, between a preceding samadhi, state of concentration,

98
00:12:37,921 --> 00:12:44,246
and succeeding one between the preceding act of intelligence and succeeding one.

99
00:12:45,148 --> 00:12:53,317
Only then will there be successive and ascending stages of maturity in the yogi state of intelligence.

100
00:12:53,856 --> 00:13:04,467
Megha and Kalanyana, knowledge of the path and instruction, are attained only when there is this kind of gathering momentum.

101
00:13:05,106 --> 00:13:22,932
the meditative process is like that of producing fire by energetically and unremittingly rubbing two sticks of wood together so as to attain the necessary intensity of heat when the flame arises.

102
00:13:25,155 --> 00:13:34,809
In the same way, the noting in Vipassana meditation should be continual and unremitting without any resting interval

103
00:13:35,195 --> 00:13:39,519
between acts of noting whatever phenomena may arise.

104
00:13:40,181 --> 00:13:58,743
For instance, if a sensation of itchiness intervenes and the yogi desires to stretch because it is hard to bear, both the sensations and the desire to get rid of it should be noted, without immediately getting rid of the sensations by stretching.

105
00:14:01,566 --> 00:14:04,830
If one goes on perseveringly noting this,

106
00:14:05,265 --> 00:14:15,777
the itchingness may generally disappear, in which case one reverts to noting the rising and falling of the abdomen.

107
00:14:15,797 --> 00:14:23,666
If the itchingness does not in fact disappear, one has, of course, to eliminate it by stretching.

108
00:14:24,626 --> 00:14:29,231
But first, the desire to do so should be noted.

109
00:14:29,818 --> 00:14:51,321
All the movements involved in the process of eliminating this sensation should be noted, especially the touching, pulling and pushing and stretching movements with an eventual reversion to noting the rising and falling of the abdomen.

110
00:14:52,870 --> 00:15:14,272
Every time you make a change of posture, you begin with noting your intention or desire to make the change and go on to noting every movement closely, such as rising from the sitting posture, raising the arm, moving and stretching it.

111
00:15:16,173 --> 00:15:21,460
You should make the change at the same time as noting the movements involved.

112
00:15:22,097 --> 00:15:25,081
As your body sways forward, note it.

113
00:15:26,042 --> 00:15:30,005
As you rise, the body becomes light and rises.

114
00:15:30,886 --> 00:15:37,373
Concentrating your mind on this, you should gently note as rising, rising.

115
00:15:38,433 --> 00:15:43,519
The yogi should behave as if he were a weak invalid.

116
00:15:44,320 --> 00:15:49,725
People in normal health rise easily and quickly or abruptly.

117
00:15:50,363 --> 00:15:56,870
Not so with feeble invalids who do so slowly and gently.

118
00:15:57,471 --> 00:16:08,383
The same is the case with people suffering from backache who rise gently lest the back hurt and cause pain.

119
00:16:09,924 --> 00:16:13,087
So also with meditating yogis.

120
00:16:13,107 --> 00:16:18,514
They have to make their changes of posture gradually and gently.

121
00:16:19,017 --> 00:16:24,802
Only then will mindfulness, concentration and insight be good.

122
00:16:25,744 --> 00:16:30,629
Begin, therefore, with gentle and gradual movements.

123
00:16:31,330 --> 00:16:41,500
When rising, the yogi must do so gently like an invalid, at the same time noting as rising, rising.

124
00:16:42,160 --> 00:16:47,606
Not only this, though the eye sees, the yogi must act

125
00:16:47,822 --> 00:16:49,423
as if he does not see.

126
00:16:50,164 --> 00:16:58,253
Similarly, when the ear hears, while meditating, the yogi's concern is only to note.

127
00:16:58,852 --> 00:17:02,917
What he sees or hears are not his concern.

128
00:17:03,697 --> 00:17:15,888
So whatever strange or striking things he may see or hear, he must behave as if he does not see or hear them, merely noting carefully.

129
00:17:17,876 --> 00:17:36,957
When making bodily movements, the yogi should do so gradually as if he were a weak invalid, gently moving the arms and legs, bending or stretching them, bending down the head and bringing it up.

130
00:17:37,897 --> 00:17:41,161
All these movements should be made gently.

131
00:17:41,922 --> 00:17:47,007
When rising from the sitting posture, he should do so gradually.

132
00:17:47,407 --> 00:18:12,285
noting as rising, rising When straightening up and standing note as standing, standing When looking here and there note as looking, seeing When walking, note the steps whether they are taken with the right or the left foot

133
00:18:12,957 --> 00:18:20,846
You must be aware of all the successive movements involved, from the raising of the foot to the dropping of it.

134
00:18:21,507 --> 00:18:27,734
Note each step taken, whether with the right foot or the left foot.

135
00:18:28,315 --> 00:18:31,940
This is the manner of noting when one walks fast.

136
00:18:34,182 --> 00:18:40,108
It will be enough if you note thus when walking fast and walking some distance.

137
00:18:40,990 --> 00:18:42,271
When walking slowly,

138
00:18:42,758 --> 00:18:50,924
or doing the Sankama walk, walking up and down, three movements should be noted in each step.

139
00:18:51,925 --> 00:19:02,895
When the foot is raised, when it is pushed forward, and when it is dropped, begin with noting the raising and dropping movements.

140
00:19:03,916 --> 00:19:07,820
One must be properly aware of the raising of the foot.

141
00:19:08,601 --> 00:19:11,584
Similarly, when the foot is dropped,

142
00:19:12,188 --> 00:19:16,853
one should be properly aware of the heavy falling of the foot.

143
00:19:18,153 --> 00:19:23,538
One must walk noting as raising, dropping with each step.

144
00:19:24,240 --> 00:19:28,765
This noting will become easier after about two days.

145
00:19:29,404 --> 00:19:39,555
Then go on to noting the three movements as described above as raising, pushing forward, dropping.

146
00:19:39,595 --> 00:19:41,217
In the beginning,

147
00:19:41,517 --> 00:20:10,089
it will suffice to note one or two movements only thus right step left step when walking fast and raising dropping when walking slowly if when walking thus you want to sit down note as wanting to sit down wanting to sit down when actually sitting down note concentratedly

148
00:20:10,541 --> 00:20:13,005
the heavy falling of your body.

149
00:20:15,627 --> 00:20:22,035
When you are seated, note the movements involved in arranging your legs and arms.

150
00:20:23,076 --> 00:20:35,451
When there are no such movements but just a stillness, static rest of the body, note the rising and falling of the abdomen.

151
00:20:35,471 --> 00:20:39,756
While noting thus, and if stiffness of your

152
00:20:39,971 --> 00:20:46,218
and sensation of heat in any part of your body arise, go on to note them.

153
00:20:46,877 --> 00:20:50,161
Then back to rising, falling.

154
00:20:51,122 --> 00:21:02,211
While noting thus, if a desire to lie down arises, note it and the movements of your legs and arms as you lie down.

155
00:21:02,231 --> 00:21:08,258
The raising of the arm, the moving of it, the resting of the elbow on the floor,

156
00:21:08,608 --> 00:21:21,801
the swaying of the body, the stretching of the legs, the listing of the body as one slowly prepares to lie down, all these movements should be noted.

157
00:21:24,023 --> 00:21:27,928
To note as you lie down thus is important.

158
00:21:27,948 --> 00:21:37,317
In the course of this movement, that is lying down, you can gain a distinctive knowledge, that is mega jnana,

159
00:21:37,599 --> 00:21:43,547
and hlanyana, the knowledge of the path and its fruition.

160
00:21:43,567 --> 00:21:54,460
When samadhi, concentration, and jnana, insight, are strong, the distinctive knowledge can come at any moment.

161
00:21:55,760 --> 00:22:05,673
It can come in a single bend of the arm or in a single stretch of the arm.

162
00:22:05,692 --> 00:22:07,454
Thus, it was that

163
00:22:07,739 --> 00:22:11,003
the Venerable Ananda become an Arhat.

164
00:22:12,425 --> 00:22:22,619
The Venerable Ananda was trying strenuously to attain Arhatship overnight on the eve of the first Buddhist Council.

165
00:22:23,260 --> 00:22:37,240
He was practicing the whole night the form of Vipassana meditation known as Kaya Pitta Sati, noting his steps, right and left, raising, pushing forward,

166
00:22:37,404 --> 00:22:49,644
and rubbing of the feet, noting happening by happening the mental desire to walk and the physical movement involved in walking.

167
00:22:50,545 --> 00:22:59,818
Although this went on till it was nearly dawn, he had not yet succeeded in attaining arhatship.

168
00:22:59,838 --> 00:23:05,708
Realizing that he had practiced the walking meditation to excess and that

169
00:23:06,109 --> 00:23:17,441
In order to balance samadhi and viriya , he should practice meditation in the lying posture for a while.

170
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:19,962
He ended his chamber.

171
00:23:20,784 --> 00:23:24,748
He sat on the couch and then lay himself down.

172
00:23:25,548 --> 00:23:34,277
While doing so and noting lying, lying, he attained arhatship in an instant.

173
00:23:36,586 --> 00:23:51,268
The Venerable Ananda was only a Sotapanna, that is, a stream-winner or one who has attained the first stage of the path to Nirvana, before he thus laid himself down.

174
00:23:51,909 --> 00:24:04,669
From Sotapanna-hood he continued to meditate and reached Sakadagami-hood, that is, the condition of the once-returner or one who has attained

175
00:24:04,919 --> 00:24:26,018
the second stage on the path, anagamikut, that is, the state of the non-returner or one who has attained the third stage on the path, and arhatship, that is, the condition of the noble one who has attained the last stage on the path.

176
00:24:26,038 --> 00:24:32,463
Reaching these three successive stages of the higher path took only a little while.

177
00:24:33,203 --> 00:24:34,925
Just think of this example

178
00:24:35,227 --> 00:24:38,829
of the Venerable Ananda's attainment of arhatship.

179
00:24:39,691 --> 00:24:45,676
Such attainment can come at any moment and need not take long.

180
00:24:47,959 --> 00:24:53,242
That is why the yogi should note with diligence all the time.

181
00:24:53,262 --> 00:25:00,049
He should not relax in his noting, thinking this little lapse should not matter much.

182
00:25:01,090 --> 00:25:03,833
All movements involved in lying down

183
00:25:03,998 --> 00:25:11,587
and arranging the arms and legs should be carefully and unremittingly noted.

184
00:25:12,348 --> 00:25:21,540
If there is no movement but only stillness of the body, go back to noting the rising and falling of the abdomen.

185
00:25:22,281 --> 00:25:28,348
Even when it is getting late and time for sleep, the yogi should not go to sleep yet.

186
00:25:28,930 --> 00:25:31,313
Dropping is noting.

187
00:25:31,333 --> 00:25:32,654
A really serious

188
00:25:32,887 --> 00:25:40,775
An energetic yogi should practice mindfulness as if he were foregoing his sleep altogether.

189
00:25:41,375 --> 00:25:45,640
He should go on meditating till he falls asleep.

190
00:25:46,921 --> 00:25:52,266
If the meditation is good and has the upper hand, he will not fall asleep.

191
00:25:53,207 --> 00:25:59,152
If on the other hand drowsiness has the upper hand, he will fall asleep.

192
00:26:00,594 --> 00:26:02,035
When he feels sleepy,

193
00:26:02,368 --> 00:26:24,232
he should note as sleepy, sleepy, if his eyelids droop, drooping, if they become heavy or leaden, heavy, if the eyes become smarting, smarting, noting thus the drowsiness may pass and the eyes become clear again.

194
00:26:24,272 --> 00:26:30,839
The yogi should then note as clear, clear,

195
00:26:31,309 --> 00:26:36,917
and go on to note the rising and falling of the Atman.

196
00:26:36,938 --> 00:26:47,291
However, perseveringly the yogi may go on meditating, if real drowsiness intervenes, he does fall asleep.

197
00:26:48,213 --> 00:26:50,917
It is not difficult to fall asleep.

198
00:26:51,498 --> 00:26:53,381
In fact, it is easy.

199
00:26:54,102 --> 00:27:01,231
If you meditate in the lying posture, you gradually become drowsy and eventually fall

200
00:27:01,414 --> 00:27:11,609
That is why the beginner in meditation should not meditate too much in the lying position.

201
00:27:12,771 --> 00:27:19,501
He should meditate much more in the sitting and walking postures of the body.

202
00:27:20,202 --> 00:27:31,219
But as it grows late and becomes time for sleep, he should meditate in the lying position, noting the rising and falling movements of the abdomen.

203
00:27:31,772 --> 00:27:36,298
he will then naturally, automatically fall asleep.

204
00:27:37,701 --> 00:27:42,247
The time he is asleep is the resting time for the yogi.

205
00:27:43,327 --> 00:27:50,458
But for the really serious yogi, he should limit his sleeping time to about four hours.

206
00:27:51,138 --> 00:27:55,503
This is the midnight time permitted by the Buddha.

207
00:27:55,525 --> 00:27:58,167
Four hours sleep is quite enough.

208
00:27:59,042 --> 00:28:08,433
If the beginner in meditation thinks that four hours sleep is not enough for health, he may extend it to five or six hours.

209
00:28:09,174 --> 00:28:12,519
Six hours sleep is clearly enough for health.

210
00:28:14,980 --> 00:28:20,627
When a yogi awakens, he should at once resume noting.

211
00:28:20,647 --> 00:28:25,894
The yogi who is really bent on attaining Megha and Kalanyana

212
00:28:26,109 --> 00:28:31,659
should rest from the meditational effort only when he is asleep.

213
00:28:32,559 --> 00:28:40,673
At other times in his waking movements, he should be noting continually and without rest.

214
00:28:40,692 --> 00:28:51,229
That is why, as soon as he awakens, he should note the awakening state of his mind as awakening, awakening.

215
00:28:51,249 --> 00:28:53,873
If he cannot yet make himself aware of this,

216
00:28:54,207 --> 00:28:58,711
he should begin noting the rising and falling of the abdomen.

217
00:28:59,913 --> 00:29:07,041
If he intends to get up from bed, he should note as intending to get up, intending to get up.

218
00:29:08,463 --> 00:29:16,794
He should then go on to note the changing movements he makes as he arranges his arms and legs.

219
00:29:17,755 --> 00:29:23,521
When he raises his head and rises, note as rising, rising

220
00:29:24,261 --> 00:29:29,688
When he is seated, note as sitting, sitting.

221
00:29:31,049 --> 00:29:38,979
If he makes any changing movements as he arranges his arms and legs, all of these movements should also be noted.

222
00:29:39,759 --> 00:29:50,893
If there are no such changes, but only a sitting quietly, he should revert to noting the rising and falling movements of the abdomen.

223
00:29:52,914 --> 00:30:00,522
One should also note when one washes one's face and when one takes a bath.

224
00:30:00,542 --> 00:30:08,570
As the movements involved in these acts are rather quick, as many of them should be noted as possible.

225
00:30:09,432 --> 00:30:16,578
There are then acts of dressing, of tidying up the bed, of opening and closing the door.

226
00:30:16,618 --> 00:30:22,365
All these should also be noted as closely as possible.

227
00:30:23,981 --> 00:30:32,851
When the yogi has his meal and looks at the meal table, he should notice, looking, seeing, looking, seeing.

228
00:30:34,051 --> 00:30:53,009
When he extends his arm towards the food, touches it, collects and arranges it, handles it and brings it to the mouth, bends his head and puts the morsel of food into his mouth, drops his arm and raises his head again,

229
00:30:53,412 --> 00:30:58,296
All these movements should be duly noted.

230
00:30:58,316 --> 00:31:03,161
This way of noting is in accordance with the Burmese way of taking a meal.

231
00:31:03,821 --> 00:31:11,909
Those who use fork and spoon or chopsticks should note the movements in an appropriate manner.

232
00:31:14,010 --> 00:31:19,076
When he chews the food, he should notice chewing, chewing.

233
00:31:19,935 --> 00:31:22,878
When he comes to know the taste of the food,

234
00:31:23,212 --> 00:31:26,135
he should note this, knowing, knowing.

235
00:31:26,155 --> 00:31:35,507
As he relishes the food and swallows it, as the food goes down his throat, he should note all these happenings.

236
00:31:36,407 --> 00:31:43,194
This is how the yogi should note as he takes one morsel after another of his food.

237
00:31:43,915 --> 00:31:52,005
As he takes his soup, all the movements involved, such as extending of the arm, handling of the spoon,

238
00:31:52,323 --> 00:31:57,689
and scooping with it and so on, all these should be noted.

239
00:31:58,368 --> 00:32:06,198
To note thus at new times is rather difficult as there are so many things to observe and note.

240
00:32:06,999 --> 00:32:16,248
The beginning yogi is likely to miss several things which he should note, but he should resolve to note all.

241
00:32:17,430 --> 00:32:18,651
He cannot of course

242
00:32:19,036 --> 00:32:22,358
help it if he overlooks and misses some.

243
00:32:22,980 --> 00:32:31,428
But as his samadhi concentration becomes strong, he will be able to note closely all these happenings.

244
00:32:33,289 --> 00:32:37,513
Well, I have mentioned so many things for the yogi to note.

245
00:32:38,255 --> 00:32:42,659
But to summarize, there are only a few things to note.

246
00:32:43,279 --> 00:32:48,704
When walking fast, notice right step, left step.

247
00:32:49,224 --> 00:32:53,388
as raising, dropping, when walking slowly.

248
00:32:54,670 --> 00:33:00,234
When sitting quietly, just note the rising and falling of the abdomen.

249
00:33:01,375 --> 00:33:06,942
Note the same when you are lying, if there is nothing particular to note.

250
00:33:07,642 --> 00:33:15,789
While noting thus, and if the mind wanders, note the acts of consciousness that arise.

251
00:33:16,157 --> 00:33:19,682
back to the rising and falling of the abdomen.

252
00:33:20,363 --> 00:33:28,173
Note also the sensation of stiffness, pain and ache and itchiness as they arise.

253
00:33:28,973 --> 00:33:33,619
Then back to the rising and falling of the abdomen.

254
00:33:34,821 --> 00:33:43,633
Note also as they arise the bending and stretching and moving of the limbs, bending and raising of the head,

255
00:33:44,051 --> 00:33:52,044
swaying and straightening of the body, then back to the rising and falling of the abdomen.

256
00:33:53,425 --> 00:34:00,134
As the yogi goes on noting thus, he will be able to note more and more of these happenings.

257
00:34:00,816 --> 00:34:11,612
In the beginning, as his mind wanders here and there, the yogi may miss noting many things, but he should not be disheartened.

258
00:34:12,199 --> 00:34:29,137
Every beginner in meditation encounters the same difficulty, but as he becomes more practiced he becomes aware of every act of mind-wandering till eventually the mind does not wander any more.

259
00:34:30,018 --> 00:34:38,206
The mind is then riveted on the object of its attention, the act of mindfulness becoming almost

260
00:34:38,440 --> 00:34:47,891
simultaneous with the object of its attention, such as the rising and falling of the abdomen.

261
00:34:49,014 --> 00:35:02,652
In other words, the rising of the abdomen becomes concurrent with the act of noting it and similarly with the falling of the abdomen.

262
00:35:02,672 --> 00:35:07,197
The physical object of attention and the mental act of noting

263
00:35:07,414 --> 00:35:09,838
are occurring as a pair.

264
00:35:10,800 --> 00:35:25,161
There is in this occurrence no person or individual involved, only this physical object of attention and the mental act of noting occurring as a pair.

265
00:35:25,882 --> 00:35:33,034
The yogi will in time actually and personally experience these occurrences.

266
00:35:33,503 --> 00:35:51,327
While noting the rising and falling of the abdomen, he will come to distinguish the rising of the abdomen as physical phenomena and the mental act of noting of it as psychical phenomena, similarly with the falling of the abdomen.

267
00:35:52,528 --> 00:36:01,079
Thus, the yogi will distinctly come to realize the simultaneous occurrence in pair of these

268
00:36:01,398 --> 00:36:03,719
psychophysical phenomena.

269
00:36:05,521 --> 00:36:25,123
Thus, with every act of noting, the yogi will come to know for himself clearly that there are only this material quality which is the object of awareness or attention and the mental quality that makes a note of it.

270
00:36:26,384 --> 00:36:29,768
This discriminating knowledge is called

271
00:36:30,119 --> 00:36:37,028
Nama Rupa Prithida Jnana, the beginning of the Vibhasana Jnana.

272
00:36:37,891 --> 00:36:43,119
It is important to gain this knowledge correctly.

273
00:36:43,139 --> 00:36:57,239
This will be succeeded, as the yogi goes on, by a knowledge that distinguishes between the cause and its effect, which knowledge is called Pasiya Parigya Jnana.

274
00:36:58,637 --> 00:37:08,286
As the yogi goes on noting, he will see for himself that what arises passes away after a short while.

275
00:37:08,306 --> 00:37:20,818
Ordinary people assume that both the material and the mental phenomena go on lasting throughout life, that is, from youth to adulthood.

276
00:37:21,739 --> 00:37:23,940
In fact, that is not so.

277
00:37:25,141 --> 00:37:27,885
There is no phenomenon that lasts

278
00:37:28,371 --> 00:37:30,293
forever.

279
00:37:30,313 --> 00:37:40,605
All phenomena arise and pass away so rapidly that they do not last even for the twinkling of an eye.

280
00:37:41,726 --> 00:37:46,972
The yogi will come to know this for himself as he goes on noting.

281
00:37:47,733 --> 00:37:54,139
He will then become convinced of the impermanency of all such phenomena.

282
00:37:54,739 --> 00:37:58,023
Such conviction is called anissa

283
00:37:58,206 --> 00:38:00,009
nupasana jnana.

284
00:38:00,829 --> 00:38:14,487
This knowledge will be succeeded by dokha nupasana jnana, which realizes that all this impermanency is suffering.

285
00:38:14,507 --> 00:38:25,922
The yogi is also likely to encounter all kinds of hardship in his body, which is just an aggregate of sufferings.

286
00:38:26,822 --> 00:38:28,045
This is also

287
00:38:28,429 --> 00:38:31,472
tokha, nupasana, jnana.

288
00:38:32,333 --> 00:38:48,871
Next, the yogi will become convinced that all these psychophysical phenomena are occurring of their own accord, following nobody's will and subject to nobody's control.

289
00:38:49,711 --> 00:38:54,918
They constitute no individual or ego entity.

290
00:38:55,617 --> 00:38:57,340
This realization is

291
00:38:57,623 --> 00:39:00,465
anatta, nupasana, jnana.

292
00:39:02,889 --> 00:39:16,844
When, as he goes on meditating, the yogi comes to realize firmly that all these phenomena are anissa, dokha, and anatta, he will attain nirvana.

293
00:39:17,565 --> 00:39:26,414
All the former Buddhas, arahants, and aviyas realized nirvana following this very path.

294
00:39:26,952 --> 00:39:54,867
All meditating yogis should recognize that they themselves are now on this Satipatthana path in fulfillment of their wish for attainment of Megayana, knowledge of the path, Palaayana, knowledge of the fruition of the path, and Nibbana Dhamma, and following the rabbining of their Parmi,

295
00:39:55,369 --> 00:39:57,172
perfection of virtue.

296
00:39:57,952 --> 00:40:19,858
They should feel glad at this and at the prospect of experiencing the noble kind of samadhi, tranquility of mind brought about by concentration and jnana, supramunding knowledge or wisdom, experienced by the Buddhas, Arhats and Aryas

297
00:40:20,092 --> 00:40:25,320
and which they themselves have never experienced before.

298
00:40:26,942 --> 00:40:42,525
It will not be long before they will experience for themselves the Meghanyana, Thalanyana and Nibbana Dhamma experienced by the Buddhas, Arhats and Aryas.

299
00:40:43,746 --> 00:40:49,574
As a matter of fact, these may be experienced in the space of a month

300
00:40:50,197 --> 00:40:54,623
or of twenty or fifteen days of their meditational practice.

301
00:40:55,925 --> 00:41:04,978
Those whose parami is exceptional may experience these dharmas even within seven days.

302
00:41:07,121 --> 00:41:18,836
The yogi should therefore rest content in the faith that he will attain these dharmas in the time specified above, that he will be freed of

303
00:41:19,322 --> 00:41:32,778
sakhyadity, ego-belief, and physiketcha, doubt or uncertainty, and saved from the danger of rebirth in the nirvana worlds.

304
00:41:34,141 --> 00:41:41,009
He should go on with his meditational practice in this faith.

305
00:41:41,028 --> 00:41:47,135
May you all be able to practice meditation well and quickly attain that nirvana

306
00:41:47,351 --> 00:41:52,965
which the Buddhas, Arhats and Aryas have experienced.

307
00:41:54,208 --> 00:41:58,358
Sadhu, Sadhu, Sadhu.

